cff-version: 1.2.0
message: "If you use this work, please cite it as below."
title: >-
  Embodied XAI Is All You Need: Revealing hidden preferences of
  vision–language models that leak into quadruped movement using XAI methods
authors:
  - family-names: Halim
    given-names: S.
    affiliation: University of Washington
abstract: >-
  A hierarchical planner–controller system in which a frozen Qwen2.5-VL-3B
  vision–language model acts as a slow planner (3 Hz) issuing continuous
  velocity commands to a PPO locomotion policy driving a simulated Unitree Go2
  quadruped (Genesis physics engine). The planner uses an adapted MEM-style
  hybrid memory — short-term video (last 4 onboard frames ~0.33 s apart) and
  long-term compressed language memory rewritten each step — to maintain
  temporal context across the closed-loop episode. The project tests whether
  human associations absorbed by the VLM (e.g. "friendly" → blue, "hostile" →
  red) leak into physical motion, and whether 4D saliency (integrated gradients
  on the chosen steering token, projected through depth into the 3D arena) can
  detect and visualise the leak. A 2×2 MEM-architecture ablation (single-frame
  vs. video × no-memory vs. +text-memory) reveals how each memory component
  shapes which environmental details drive the agent's decisions.
keywords:
  - explainable AI
  - embodied AI
  - vision-language models
  - quadruped locomotion
  - reinforcement learning
  - saliency
  - integrated gradients
  - MEM memory
license: MIT
date-released: 2025-01-01
